<h1>Summary of trigonometric identities</h1>

<br><br>
<table cellpadding=3D"5">
<tbody><tr><td colspan=3D"2">You have seen quite a few trigonometric identi=
ties in the past few pages. It is convenient to have a summary of them for =
reference.  These identities mostly refer to one angle denoted <i>&#952;</i=
>, but there are some that involve two angles, and for those, the two angle=
s are denoted <i>&#945;</i> and <i>&#946;</i>.</td></tr>

<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr><td colspan=3D"2"><h4>The more important identities.</h4>=20
You don=92t have to know all the identities off the top of your head.  But =
these you should.</td></tr>

<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/defining.jpg" wi=
dth=3D"440"></td>
<td><b>Defining relations</b> for tangent, cotangent, secant, and cosecant =
in terms of sine and cosine.</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/pythagorean.jpg"=
 width=3D"200"></td>
<td><b>The Pythagorean formula for sines and cosines.</b>=20
This is probably the most important trig identity.</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/complementary.jp=
g" width=3D"440"></td>
<td><b>Identities expressing trig functions in terms of their complements.<=
/b>
There's not much to these.  Each of the six trig functions is equal to its =
co-function evaluated at the complementary angle.</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/periodicity.jpg"=
 width=3D"280"></td>
<td><b>Periodicity of trig functions.</b> =20
Sine, cosine, secant, and cosecant have period 2<i>&#960;</i> while tangent=
 and cotangent have period <i>&#960;</i>.</td></tr>


<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/negativeidentiti=
es.jpg" width=3D"250"></td>
<td><b>Identities for negative angles.</b> =20
Sine, tangent, cotangent, and cosecant are odd functions while cosine and s=
ecant are even functions.</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/sumformulas.jpg"=
 width=3D"400"></td>
<td><b>Sum and difference formulas for sine and cosine.</b></td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/doublesine.jpg" =
width=3D"225"></td>
<td rowspan=3D"2"><b>Double angle formulas for sine and cosine.</b>
Note that there are three forms for the double angle formula for cosine.  Y=
ou only need to know one, but be able to derive the other two from the Pyth=
agorean formula.</td></tr>
<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/doublecosine.jpg=
" width=3D"275"></td></tr>

<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr><td colspan=3D"2"><h4>The less important identities.</h4>
You should know that there are these identities, but they are not as import=
ant as those mentioned above.  They can all be derived from those above, bu=
t sometimes it takes a bit of work to do so.</td></tr>

<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/secantpythagorea=
n.jpg" width=3D"200"></td>
<td><b>The Pythagorean formula for tangents and secants.</b>
There=92s also one for cotangents and cosecants, but as cotangents and cose=
cants are rarely needed, it=92s unnecessary.</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/supplementary.jp=
g" width=3D"250"></td>
<td><b>Identities expressing trig functions in terms of their supplements.<=
/b></td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/tangentformulas.=
jpg" width=3D"300"></td>
<td><b>Sum, difference, and double angle formulas for tangent.</b>
</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/halfangleformula=
s.jpg" width=3D"300"></td>
<td><b>The half angle formulas.</b>
The ones for sine and cosine take the positive or negative square root depe=
nding on the quadrant of the angle <i>&#952;</i>/2. For example, if <i>&#95=
2;</i>/2 is an acute angle, then the positive root would be used.
</td></tr>


<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr><td colspan=3D"2"><h4>Truly obscure identities.</h4>
These are just here for perversity. No, not really. They have some applicat=
ions, but they=92re usually narrow applications, and they could just as wel=
l be forgotten until  needed.

</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/productsum.jpg" =
width=3D"350"></td>
<td><b>Product-sum identities.</b>
This group of identities allow you to change a sum or difference of sines o=
r cosines into a product of sines and cosines.
</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/productidentitie=
s.jpg" width=3D"350"></td>
<td><b>Product identities.</b>
Aside: weirdly enough, these product identities were used before logarithms=
 were invented in order to perform multiplication.  Here=92s how you could =
use the second one. If you want to multiply <i>x</i> times <i>y,</i> use a =
table to look up the angle <i>&#945;</i> whose cosine is <i>x</i> and the a=
ngle <i>&#946;</i> whose cosine is <i>y</i>.  Look up the cosines of the su=
m <i>&#945;</i>&nbsp;+&nbsp;<i>&#946;</i>. and the difference <i>&#945;&nbs=
p;=96&nbsp;&#946;</i>.  Average those two cosines.  You get the product <i>=
xy</i>!  Three table look-ups, and computing a sum, a difference, and an av=
erage rather than one multiplication.  Tycho Brahe (1546=961601), among oth=
ers, used this algorithm known as <i>prosthaphaeresis.</i>
</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/triple.jpg" widt=
h=3D"250"></td>
<td><b>Triple angle formulas.</b>
You can easily reconstruct these from the addition  and double angle formul=
as.
</td></tr>

<tr><td><img src=3D"https://mathcs.clarku.edu/~djoyce/trig/weierstrass.jpg"=
 width=3D"225"></td>
<td><b>More half-angle formulas.</b>
These describe the basic trig functions in terms of the tangent of half the=
 angle. These are used in calculus for a particular kind of substitution in=
 integrals sometimes called the Weierstrass <i>t</i>-substitution.
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

